1":"1271","1192":"1192","after 1216":"na 1216","1248":"1248","1210":"1210","about 1210":"circa 1210","1209":"1209","Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1172–Jan 1243":"1172–1248","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1192–1230":"1192–1230","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1220–1271":"1220–1271","–1248":"–1248","1110–1153":"1110–1153","1150–1209":"1150–1209","vers 1209":"about 1209","1220":"1220","1110":"1110","1230":"1230","1153":"1153","Jan 1243":"1248","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","1271":"1271","1192":"1192","after 1216":"after 1216","1248":"1248","1210":"1210","about 1210":"about 1210","1209":"1209","Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mello","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Adelino, Ana, Joaquin, Acacio, Claudio, Cristina, Fernando, Americo, Enrique.  Portuguese Duarte, Joaquim, Armanda, Joao, Paulo, Serafim.","Italian: probably from a short form of a personal name ending with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-ello</i>, such as <i>Giacomello</i> from   Giacomo  .","Portuguese: variant of   Melo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giacomo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenico, Gino, Salvatore.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giacomo</i>, from Latin <i>Jacobus</i> via Late Latin <i>Jacomus</i> (see   James   and   Jacob  )."]},{"name":"Melle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Horst, Kurt, Otto.","Italian: habitational name from Melle in Cuneo province (Piedmont); in some cases possibly also a variant of a personal name such as   Mello   1.","Norwegian: probably a variant of   Mele  ."]},{"name":"Mellone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Emidio, Luigi, Pasquale.","Italian: from an augmentative of   Mello  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume I de Mello Seigneur de St Bris was born in 1172, in Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Dreux IV de Mello, was 63 and his mother, Ermengarde de SAINT-BRIS, was 11169. He married Élisabeth DE MONT-SAINT-JEAN after 1216. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1248, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1172–Jan 1243":"1172–1248","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1192–1230":"1192–1230","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1220–1271":"1220–1271","–1248":"–1248","1110–1153":"1110